The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Oct. 1: A court today directed the Delhi police special cell to hand over a copy of the FIR to arrested Maoist leader Khobad Ghandy.          
	That is his right, the court said, rejecting arguments from the police that they were under no legal obligation to provide him with a copy of the FIR. A copy of the FIR will help Ghandys legal team firm up his defence.                   
	 Dhaka (PTI): The top-most Lashkar-e-Toiba militant in Bangladesh, overseeing the groups militant movements across the Indian border, was arrested on Wednesday. Emdadullah alias Mahbub, 28, who had sneaked into Bangladesh in 2006 after escaping from the custody of Bengal police, was also involved in smuggling bomb-making material across the border, police said.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): A London-bound British Airways plane with 250 passengers on-board made an emergency landing in Mumbai on Thursday. The aircraft returned to Chhatrapati Shivaji International Airport after the fire alarm in the cockpit went off soon after take-off.                  
	 Lahore (PTI): Pakistan has signed a memorandum of understanding to provide road and rail transit facilities to India for its trade with Afghanistan, commerce minister Makhdoom Amin Fahim has said. Pakistan had earlier been reluctant to grant Delhi transit facilities for trade with Kabul as it felt that would have benefited only India.                  
	 Hathras (PTI): Forty-seven persons have been arrested and around two thousand booked in connection with the torching of 11 coaches of the Delhi-bound Mahananda Express at Uttar Pradeshs Hathras railway station on Wednesday.                  
	 Islamabad (PTI): Eleven Indian fishermen have been arrested by Pakistan for allegedly violating the countrys territorial waters. The fishermen, on two boats, said they had transgressed by mistake.
                                                                                                                           
